      "text": "Okay, this error message is much better! It means Bitcoin Core successfully loaded the configuration file, but it\u0027s telling you about specific settings that need to be placed in the network-specific section to work correctly for the network you\u0027re running on (testnet).\n\n```\nconfig setting for -port only applied on test network when in [test] section.\nconfig setting for -rpcbind only applied on test network when in [test] section.\n```\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n*   You have `testnet\u003d1` uncommented, so your node is running on the testnet (specifically testnet3, which the config file refers to as `[test]`).\n*   Bitcoin Core\u0027s configuration file allows you to set options that apply *only* to a specific network by placing them under a `[network]` header (like `[main]`, `[test]`, `[testnet4]`, etc.).\n*   Certain network-specific settings, like the P2P listening `port` and the RPC binding `rpcbind`, **must** be placed under the correct network section (`[test]` in your case) if you want them to apply when you are running on that network.\n*   You likely have `port\u003d` and `rpcbind\u003d` uncommented somewhere *before* any of the `[network]` sections (`[main]`, `[test]`, etc.) in your `bitcoin.conf`. Bitcoin Core is telling you it\u0027s ignoring those settings for testnet because they aren\u0027t in the `[test]` section.\n\n**How to Fix This:**\n\n1.  **Open your `bitcoin.conf` file** in the testnet data directory again (`%APPDATA%\\Bitcoin\\testnet3\\bitcoin.conf`).\n2.  **Find the lines `port\u003d18333`** (or whatever port you might have set) and **`rpcbind\u003d127.0.0.1`**. These are currently somewhere above the `[main]`, `[test]`, etc., sections.\n3.  **Find the `[test]` section header** in the file.\n4.  **Cut** the `port\u003d` and `rpcbind\u003d` lines from where they are now.\n5.  **Paste** these lines *under* the `[test]` section header.\n\n**Example:**\n\nYour file might currently look something like this (simplified):\n\n```ini\n# ... other general options ...\nserver\u003d1\ntestnet\u003d1\nrpcuser\u003dplayer3m49\nrpcpassword\u003dM!n3r49m1d@st0uch\nrpcallowip\u003d127.0.0.1\nrpcbind\u003d127.0.0.1  \u003c-- CUT THIS LINE\n# rpcport\u003d\u003cport\u003e # If uncommented, CUT THIS TOO\n\n# Default P2P port (likely commented out, but if uncommented...)\n# port\u003d8333\nport\u003d18333  \u003c-- CUT THIS LINE\n\n# ... more general options/comments ...\n\n[main]\n# Options for mainnet\n\n[test]\n# Options for testnet3 \u003c-- PASTE THE LINES HERE\n\n[testnet4]\n# Options for testnet4\n\n# ... etc ...\n```\n\nYou need to move those lines so it looks like this:\n\n```ini\n# ... other general options ...\nserver\u003d1\ntestnet\u003d1\nrpcuser\u003dplayer3m49\nrpcpassword\u003dM!n3r49m1d@st0uch\nrpcallowip\u003d127.0.0.1\n# rpcbind\u003d127.0.0.1  \u003c-- This line is now commented or removed from the general section\n# rpcport\u003d\u003cport\u003e # If uncommented, comment/remove from here\n\n# Default P2P port (likely commented out, but if uncommented...)\n# port\u003d8333\n# port\u003d18333  \u003c-- This line is now commented or removed from the general section\n\n# ... more general options/comments ...\n\n[main]\n# Options for mainnet\n\n[test]\n# Options for testnet3\nrpcbind\u003d127.0.0.1  \u003c-- PASTE THE LINE HERE\nport\u003d18333         \u003c-- PASTE THE LINE HERE\n# If you explicitly set rpcport, it should go here too:\n# rpcport\u003d18332\n\n[testnet4]\n# Options for testnet4\n\n# ... etc ...\n```\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **`rpcport`:** The error didn\u0027t mention `rpcport`. This is because `testnet\u003d1` automatically sets the *default* RPC port for testnet to 18332. So, you don\u0027t *need* to explicitly set `rpcport\u003d18332` if `testnet\u003d1` is already set. However, if you *did* uncomment a `rpcport\u003d` line in the general section, it\u0027s good practice to move it under `[test]` as well, or just leave it commented and rely on the default.\n*   **Other RPC Settings:** Settings like `rpcuser`, `rpcpassword`, `rpcallowip`, and `server` are *not* network-specific in the same way. They can remain in the general section at the top, and they will apply to whichever network the node is running on. Moving them under `[test]` also works and can make your config cleaner by grouping all testnet-related settings together.\n\n**After making the changes:**\n\n1.  **Save the `bitcoin.conf` file.**\n2.  **Stop and Restart Bitcoin Core.**\n3.  **Check the testnet `debug.log` again.** Look at the very beginning for config loading messages and at the end for `InitRPC` and `RPC: server started` messages listening on `127.0.0.1:18332`.\n4.  **Run your Python script again.**\n\nThis should resolve the config parsing errors and allow the RPC server to start correctly on the testnet port.",
